'''Louis Augustus "Lou" Phillips''' (24 February 1878 – 14 March 1916) was a Welsh [[rugby union|rugby]] player, who played [[Rugby union positions#Half-backs|half-back]] for [[Newport RFC]], and won four [[cap (sport)|caps]] for {{nrut|Wales}}. He was also a talented amateur [[golfer]].
Born in [[Newport, Wales|Newport]], Monmouthshire, Phillips was educated at [[Monmouth Grammar School]], leaving to become an architect. He played rugby at school and then at Newport, earning a place in the 1st XV after several players retired or defected to rugby league. He made 90 appearances for Newport, during which he developed a famous [[half-back (rugby union)|half-back]] partnership with [[Llewellyn Lloyd]]. His debut for Wales, playing alongside Lloyd, was against {{nrut|England}} in 1900, when Wales won the [[Triple Crown (rugby union)|Triple Crown]]. He earned selection again in 1901 but was forced to retire from rugby after incurring an injury playing {{nrut|Scotland}}.
Phillips enlisted in the 20th (Service) Battalion [[Royal Fusiliers]] at the start of the [[First World War]]. He was deployed to the [[Western Front (World War I)|Western Front]] in November 1915. He was shot dead while out on a [[wiring party]] on the night of 14 March 1916, near [[Cambrin]], France.
==Early life== Louis Augustus Phillips was born at Stow Hill, [[Newport, Wales|Newport]], [[Monmouthshire]] on 24 February 1878. He was educated at [[Monmouth Grammar School]]. After serving his [[articled clerk|articles]] with Huberston and Fawkner, [[architect]]s, he began practising in 1907.{{sfn|Sewell|1919|p=146}}
==Rugby career== Phillips began playing rugby while at Monmouth Grammar School. He went on to play for [[Newport RFC]], earning selection for the first team in 1897.{{sfn|Sewell|1919|p=146}} His first season at Newport was disappointing for the club, which lost seven games, after the previous six consecutive years of success. Several players had moved to Yorkshire to play [[rugby league]], while others had married and retired. Nevertheless, Phillips was one of four new players in the team to 'make an impact', alongside [[George Boots]], [[Jehoida Hodges]] and [[Reg Skrimshire]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.historyofnewport.co.uk/seasons/seasons.php?id=24|title=History of Newport RFC: 1897–1898|author=Alun Lee|publisher=}}</ref>
===Half-back partnership with Llewellyn Lloyd=== The 1897–8 season at Newport saw the beginning of a 'historic' partnership at [[half-back (rugby union)|half-back]] between Phillips and [[Llewellyn Lloyd]] that lasted till 1901.{{sfn|Sewell|1919|p=146}}{{sfn|Townsend Collins|1948|p=94}} Phillips and Lloyd were thought of as a pair, both playing along similar lines and sharing the work of scrum-half and outside-half. While Lloyd was a smarter runner, Phillips was a better kick, but both of them could drop goals, and were remarkable in their kicks to touch.{{sfn|Townsend Collins|1948|p=94}}
In the 1898–9 season, Newport suffered from further retirements: Boots and Phillips were the only 2 players to appear in all 24 matches of the season.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.historyofnewport.co.uk/seasons/seasons.php?id=000025|title=History of Newport RFC: 1898–1899|author=Alun Lee|publisher=}}</ref> During the following season, 1899–1900, with Lloyd as captain, the club was reinvigorated and scored 416 points compared with 192 in the previous season.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.historyofnewport.co.uk/seasons/seasons.php?id=26|title=History of Newport RFC: 1899–1900|author=Alun Lee|publisher=}}</ref> Phillips and Lloyd were adjudged to be the half-back pair of the season at both club and international level, even if there were some more brilliant individuals.{{sfn|Townsend Collins|1948|p=94}} In total, Phillips appeared 90 times for Newport, scoring 9 [[try|tries]], 2 [[drop goal]]s and 1 [[penalty (rugby union)|penalty]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.blackandambers.co.uk/Teams/Player?PersonId=101647|title=Lou Phillips|publisher=Newport RFC}}</ref> Townsend Collins remarked: 'He had no tricks or subtleties, but he played the orthodox game of the day with supreme success.'{{sfn|Townsend Collins|1948|p=95}}
===Wales=== Phillips, who was a strong runner and tackled well, made his international debut for Wales against {{nrut|England}} on 6 January 1900 at [[Gloucester]]. His initial selection was principally due to his partnership at Newport with Lloyd, who also made selection for Wales. Lloyd had already played in 1896 against Ireland, and against Scotland and Ireland in 1899.<ref name="EE000106" /> During the game, which Wales won 3–13, Phillips displayed 'special smartness' and used 'the acme of judgment' in his first international appearance, proving also to be a 'splendid defender'. He was reckoned to be amongst the best of the backs, and the combination with Lloyd was excellent.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://hdl.handle.net/10107/3744705|title=1st International of the Season|newspaper=South Wales Daily News|date=8 January 1900|accessdate=26 January 2016|publisher=David Duncan and Sons}}</ref> In the following match, against {{nrut|Scotland}} at Swansea on 27 January, the half-back partnership of Phillips and Lloyd continued to perform: their defensive play was 'sound', and in attack, Phillips' 'splendid' fielding and kicking to touch, matched Lloyd's 'cleverness' and 'dodging ability'. Wales was again victorious, 12–3.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://hdl.handle.net/10107/3744867|title=International Match|newspaper= South Wales Daily News|date=29 January 1900|accessdate=26 January 2016|publisher=David Duncan and Sons}}</ref> For the next game, away to {{nrut|Ireland}} at Belfast on 17 March, Lloyd was replaced by [[Selwyn Biggs]] of Cardiff. The half-back combination was not as good as with Lloyd but worked better than pundits had expected. The 0–3 victory over the Irish earned the Welsh the [[Triple Crown (rugby union)|Triple Crown]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://hdl.handle.net/10107/3745245|title=The Triple Crown |newspaper=South Wales Daily News |date=19 March 1900|accessdate=26 January 2016|publisher=David Duncan and Sons}}</ref>
Phillips missed the opening match of the 1901 international season against England due to an injury to his knee: he was replaced at the last moment by [[Bala Jones]] of [[Aberavon RFC]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://hdl.handle.net/10107/3474988|title=England v Wales |newspaper= Evening Express|date=5 January 1901|accessdate=26 January 2016|publisher=Walter Alfred Pearce}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://hdl.handle.net/10107/3474988|title= Phillips not playing |newspaper= Evening Express|date=5 January 1901|accessdate=26 January 2016|publisher=Walter Alfred Pearce}}</ref> Thinking that he had recovered, Phillips was back for the following match, against Scotland on 9 February at Inverleith, but within ten minutes he was almost helpless. He played on, and 'his last match was a tragic end to a great if short career.'{{sfn|Townsend Collins|1948|p=94}}<ref>{{cite news|url=http://hdl.handle.net/10107/3476020|title=Football gossip |newspaper=Evening Express|date=16 February 1901|accessdate=26 January 2016|publisher=Walter Alfred Pearce}}</ref> The Scottish half-backs, [[Jimmy Gillespie]] and Frank Fasson, outplayed Lloyd and Phillips, and prevented the Welsh backline from receiving much ball. Scotland beat Wales 18–8, and the Welsh defeat was blamed on the half-backs.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://hdl.handle.net/10107/3475900|title= Scotland v Wales |newspaper=Evening Express|date=11 February 1901|accessdate=26 January 2016|publisher=Walter Alfred Pearce}}</ref>
