==Golf== In 1907 and again in 1912, Phillips was Welsh Amateur golf champion. He was also runner-up for the [[Irish Amateur Open Championship]] in 1913, and in the following year, 1914, he was beaten in the sixth round of [[The Amateur Championship]].{{sfn|Sewell|1919|p=147}} Phillips also represented the Wales golf team, facing Ireland in August 1913.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Jenkins |first1=John M. |last2=Pierce |first2=Duncan|last3=Auty| first3=Timothy |title=Who's Who of Welsh International Rugby Players |year=1991 |publisher=Bridge Books |location=Wrexham |isbn=1-872424-10-4|page=127}}</ref>
==Military service and death== At the start of the [[First World War]], Phillips enlisted in the 20th (Service) Battalion [[Royal Fusiliers]], and after refusing a commission, served as a Sergeant.{{sfn|McCrery|2014|p=242}} The 20th Royal Fusiliers was one of four battalions of the regiment raised in 1914 by the Public Schools and University Men’s Force.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.longlongtrail.co.uk/army/regiments-and-corps/the-british-infantry-regiments-of-1914-1918/royal-fusiliers-city-of-london-regiment/|title=Royal Fusiliers (City of London) Regiment|work=The Long, Long Trail}}</ref> Phillips was deployed to France with his unit on 16 November 1915. On the night of 14 March 1916, while out on a [[wiring party]], he was shot through the chest and killed, near [[Cambrin]], France.{{sfn|Sewell|1919|p=146}}
He is buried in Cambrin Churchyard Extension (Grave L1 10B).<ref>{{CWGC|id=171151|name=Phillips, L A}}</ref>
